Chinaman
Homonym Number: 4
Word Class:noun
Sense Number:
Definition:an unshorn lock on a sheep's rump, reminiscent of an oriental pigtail.
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 0/0/1956
Source: Wool Away!
Author: BOWEN
Vol / Page: 155
Edition:
Quote: CHINAMAN. A lock of wool missed by the shearer and left unshorn on the sheep's rump. The shearer does not see it until the sheep has stood up and got out of the porthole.
Notes:

Date: 26/2/1965
Source: Listener (New Zealand Listener)
Author:
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote: <i>Chinaman:</i> An unshorn lock on the sheep's rump reminiscent of the pigtail worn by Orientals in earlier years.
Notes: (H.A.L. Laing)

Date: 21/2/1968
Source: Straight Furrow
Author:
Vol / Page: 20
Edition:
Quote: CHINAMAN: An unshorn lock on the sheep's rump, like the pigtail of the Orientals.
Notes: [Shearer's language]

